data.chText: 心血来潮；一时的兴致；突发的奇想
data.enText: a sudden wish to do or have sth, especially when it is sth unusual or unnecessary

data.chText: 她每次心血来潮他都不得不依随她。
data.enText: He was forced to pander to her every whim .

data.chText: 我们一时冲动买了这所房子。
data.enText: We bought the house on a whim .

data.chText: 我的职责似乎随着老板的兴致每天改变。
data.enText: My duties seem to change daily at the whim of the boss.

data.chText: 她随心所欲地雇用人和解雇人。
data.enText: She hires and fires people at whim .

tr: an odd or fanciful or capricious idea
example: the theatrical notion of disguise is associated with disaster in his stories
he had a whimsy about flying to the moon
whimsy can be humorous to someone with time to enjoy it
he bought it on an impulse

value.def: A whim is a wish to do or have something which seems to have no serious reason or purpose behind it, and often occurs suddenly.

example.ex: We decided, more or less on a whim, to sail to Morocco...
example.tran: 我们多少有点心血来潮，决定航海去摩洛哥。

example.ex: The premium can increase at the whim of the insurers...
example.tran: 保险公司可以随时提高保费。

example.ex: Lately, the president has been sacking and picking new ministers at whim.
example.tran: 最近，总统一时兴起频频解雇旧部长，选任新部长。

value.tran: 一时的兴致;心血来潮;突发的奇想
